const heartDisease = `
<p>Cardiovascular disease (CVD) causes approximately 17.9 million deaths each year — more than any other condition on earth, according to the World Health Organization. Coronary artery disease (CAD), heart failure, arrhythmias, and valvular disorders all fall under this umbrella, yet the vast majority of cases share common, addressable drivers. Understanding those drivers, recognising warning signs early, and taking evidence-based action can decisively reduce personal risk.</p>

<h2>What Is Heart Disease?</h2>
<p>CAD develops when plaque — a mixture of cholesterol, calcium, fat, and inflammatory cells — accumulates inside the coronary arteries and progressively restricts blood flow to the heart muscle. Over years, this process (atherosclerosis) may be silent, then suddenly manifest as angina, heart attack, or sudden cardiac death when a plaque ruptures and triggers an acute clot. Equally important are heart failure (the heart pumps inadequately), arrhythmias (abnormal electrical rhythms), and cardiomyopathy (intrinsic heart muscle disease), each requiring distinct management strategies.</p>

<h2>Major Risk Factors</h2>
<h3>Modifiable Risks</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Hypertension:</strong> Persistent blood pressure above 130/80 mmHg forces the heart to labour against elevated resistance, thickening its walls and accelerating arterial damage. An estimated 1.28 billion adults worldwide are hypertensive, with nearly half unaware.</li>
  <li><strong>Elevated LDL Cholesterol:</strong> LDL particles penetrate the arterial wall, oxidise, and trigger macrophage recruitment, forming the fatty streaks that evolve into unstable plaques. Optimal LDL is below 100 mg/dL; below 70 mg/dL for those with established disease.</li>
  <li><strong>Tobacco Use:</strong> Cigarette chemicals damage the endothelial lining of blood vessels, accelerate plaque formation, and promote clot formation. Smokers have 2–4 times the CAD risk of non-smokers; even secondhand smoke confers measurable harm.</li>
  <li><strong>Physical Inactivity:</strong> A sedentary lifestyle independently raises CVD risk by approximately 35%. Exercise lowers resting blood pressure, improves HDL, reduces inflammatory markers, and strengthens the heart muscle.</li>
  <li><strong>Obesity:</strong> Abdominal adiposity promotes insulin resistance, systemic inflammation, hypertension, and dyslipidaemia — a compounding quartet of cardiovascular hazard.</li>
  <li><strong>Type 2 Diabetes:</strong> Chronic hyperglycaemia glycates proteins, stiffens arterial walls, and accelerates atherosclerosis. Diabetes multiplies CVD risk by 2–4 fold.</li>
  <li><strong>Chronic Stress and Poor Sleep:</strong> Sustained psychological stress elevates cortisol and catecholamines, raising blood pressure and promoting inflammation. Fewer than 7 hours of sleep per night is independently associated with higher rates of hypertension, obesity, and cardiac events.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Non-Modifiable Risks</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Age:</strong> Atherosclerosis accumulates over decades. Significant risk begins after 45 in men and 55 in women.</li>
  <li><strong>Family History:</strong> A first-degree relative with premature CVD (men before 55, women before 65) doubles personal lifetime risk through shared genetic predispositions.</li>
  <li><strong>Sex:</strong> Men develop CAD about a decade earlier. Post-menopausal women lose oestrogen's cardioprotective effects and rapidly close this gap — heart disease is the leading killer of women in most countries.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Recognising Warning Signs</h2>
<p>CAD may be asymptomatic for decades. Symptoms, when they appear, include chest pain or tightness (angina) provoked by exertion and relieved by rest; shortness of breath; radiation of discomfort to the jaw, left arm, or upper back; unexplained fatigue; and palpitations. Heart attack symptoms are more abrupt and severe: crushing chest pressure, cold sweats, nausea, and arm pain. This is a medical emergency — call emergency services immediately. Every minute of delay equates to irreversible heart muscle loss. Women more frequently present with atypical symptoms such as fatigue, jaw pain, and nausea without chest discomfort, making awareness critical.</p>

<h2>Diagnosis</h2>
<p>Evaluation begins with history, physical examination, and blood work — lipid panel, fasting glucose, HbA1c, and high-sensitivity C-reactive protein. Electrocardiography (ECG) identifies arrhythmias, conduction abnormalities, and evidence of prior myocardial infarction. Echocardiography assesses ventricular function, wall motion, and valve integrity. Exercise stress testing reveals exertion-induced ischaemia. Coronary CT angiography provides non-invasive three-dimensional mapping of coronary anatomy. Invasive coronary angiography remains the gold standard when revascularisation is being planned.</p>

<h2>Prevention Strategies</h2>
<h3>Heart-Healthy Diet</h3>
<p>The PREDIMED randomised trial — 7,447 high-risk participants, median 4.8 years of follow-up — demonstrated that a Mediterranean diet supplemented with extra-virgin olive oil or nuts reduced major cardiovascular events by 30% versus a low-fat control diet. The Mediterranean pattern emphasises abundant vegetables, fruits, legumes, whole grains, olive oil, and fish, with minimal red meat and refined carbohydrates. The DASH diet offers parallel benefits focused on blood pressure reduction.</p>
<h3>Physical Activity</h3>
<p>Guidelines recommend ≥150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic exercise or ≥75 minutes of vigorous activity per week, plus two resistance-training sessions. Even replacing 30 minutes of daily sitting with brisk walking independently reduces all-cause and cardiovascular mortality.</p>
<h3>Smoking Cessation</h3>
<p>Within one year of quitting, excess CVD risk drops by 50%. Combination pharmacotherapy (varenicline or nicotine replacement) plus behavioural counselling produces success rates roughly double those of willpower alone.</p>

<h2>Treatment Options</h2>
<h3>Medications</h3>
<p>High-intensity statins (atorvastatin 40–80 mg, rosuvastatin 20–40 mg) are the cornerstone of LDL reduction and plaque stabilisation. ACE inhibitors or ARBs lower blood pressure and protect renal and cardiac function. Beta-blockers reduce heart rate and myocardial oxygen demand. Antiplatelet agents (aspirin, clopidogrel, ticagrelor) prevent clot formation after acute events. SGLT2 inhibitors (empagliflozin, dapagliflozin) and GLP-1 agonists (semaglutide) now demonstrate significant cardiovascular mortality reductions beyond their glucose-lowering effects, and are increasingly incorporated into heart-failure and high-risk management.</p>
<h3>Interventional Procedures</h3>
<p>Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) threads a catheter to the coronary artery, inflates a balloon to compress plaque, and deploys a drug-eluting stent to maintain patency. Coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG) creates alternative blood-flow conduits using vessels harvested from the chest or leg, and remains preferable for complex multi-vessel disease. Cardiac rehabilitation following either procedure reduces all-cause mortality by 20–26% and should be offered to all eligible patients.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>Can atherosclerosis be reversed?</h3>
<p>Full reversal is uncommon, but the REVERSAL and ASTEROID trials both demonstrated measurable plaque regression with high-intensity statin therapy. Intensive lifestyle change (Mediterranean diet, daily exercise, smoking cessation, stress management) compounds this effect significantly.</p>
<h3>Is daily aspirin still recommended for prevention?</h3>
<p>No longer for primary prevention — bleeding risk outweighs benefit in most adults who have not yet had a heart attack or stroke. Aspirin remains firmly indicated for secondary prevention after a confirmed myocardial infarction or ischaemic stroke.</p>
<h3>How does sleep affect the heart?</h3>
<p>Chronic short sleep raises blood pressure, worsens glucose control, and promotes obesity — all cardiovascular risk factors. Adults should target 7–9 hours nightly. Obstructive sleep apnoea, which causes repeated nocturnal oxygen desaturation, carries particularly elevated cardiac risk and should be evaluated and treated.</p>
<h3>At what age should I begin cardiovascular screening?</h3>
<p>The American Heart Association recommends baseline risk assessment from age 20 including blood pressure, cholesterol, glucose, and BMI. Those with risk factors or family history of premature CVD warrant earlier, more frequent assessment.</p>
<h3>What is the most impactful single lifestyle change?</h3>
<p>For smokers, quitting — CVD risk halves within one year. For non-smokers, adopting a Mediterranean or DASH dietary pattern combined with regular aerobic exercise produces the most substantial combined reduction in cardiovascular events.</p>

<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul>
  <li>World Health Organization. Cardiovascular diseases fact sheet. 2023.</li>
  <li>Estruch R, et al. Primary Prevention of Cardiovascular Disease with a Mediterranean Diet. NEJM. 2018.</li>
  <li>Virani SS, et al. Heart Disease and Stroke Statistics — 2021 Update. Circulation. 2021.</li>
  <li>Arnett DK, et al. ACC/AHA Guideline on Primary Prevention of CVD. JACC. 2019.</li>
  <li>Mayo Clinic. Heart disease — Symptoms and causes. 2023.</li>
  <li>NHLBI. Heart Disease Risk Factors. 2022.</li>
</ul>`;

const breastCancer = `
<p>Breast cancer is the most frequently diagnosed cancer among women globally, with approximately 2.3 million new cases each year. Despite its prevalence, advances in screening, molecular profiling, and targeted therapy have transformed outcomes dramatically — the five-year survival rate for localised breast cancer now exceeds 99% in many countries. Understanding risk, detecting disease early, and navigating a complex treatment landscape are three essential steps every person should be empowered to take.</p>

<h2>Types of Breast Cancer</h2>
<p>Most breast cancers originate in the milk ducts (ductal carcinoma) or lobules (lobular carcinoma). When cancer cells remain confined within these structures it is classified as in situ (non-invasive); when cells breach the basement membrane it becomes invasive. Receptor status — oestrogen receptor (ER), progesterone receptor (PR), and HER2 — determines which therapies will be effective and profoundly influences prognosis. Hormone receptor-positive (HR+) cancers represent approximately 70% of cases and respond to endocrine therapy. HER2-positive cancers are driven by overexpression of a growth-promoting protein and respond to targeted antibody therapies. Triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC) — lacking all three receptors — is more aggressive and relies predominantly on chemotherapy and emerging immunotherapy.</p>

<h2>Risk Factors</h2>
<h3>Non-Modifiable Factors</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Age and Sex:</strong> Being female is the dominant risk factor. Risk rises progressively after 40; about two-thirds of invasive cancers occur in women aged 55 and older.</li>
  <li><strong>BRCA1/BRCA2 Mutations:</strong> These inherited mutations confer a lifetime breast cancer risk of 50–72%. Testing is recommended for individuals with a strong personal or family history, male breast cancer in the family, or Ashkenazi Jewish ancestry.</li>
  <li><strong>Family History:</strong> A first-degree relative with breast cancer roughly doubles personal risk; multiple affected relatives or early-onset disease in the family increase it further.</li>
  <li><strong>Dense Breast Tissue:</strong> Women with dense breasts have four to six times higher risk than those with predominantly fatty tissue and receive less accurate mammography — a combination that underscores the value of supplemental ultrasound or MRI screening.</li>
  <li><strong>Prior Breast Conditions:</strong> Atypical ductal or lobular hyperplasia raises future risk four to five-fold.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Modifiable Factors</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Alcohol:</strong> Even one drink per day is associated with a 7–10% increase in risk. The relationship is linear — risk rises with each additional drink consumed.</li>
  <li><strong>Post-menopausal Obesity:</strong> Adipose tissue becomes the primary oestrogen source after menopause. Excess body fat elevates circulating oestrogen, promoting HR+ cancer growth.</li>
  <li><strong>Physical Inactivity:</strong> Regular exercise reduces breast cancer risk by 10–20% through effects on hormonal levels, immune function, and insulin resistance.</li>
  <li><strong>Combined Hormone Therapy:</strong> Long-term use (≥5 years) of combined oestrogen-progestogen HRT modestly increases risk. Oestrogen-only therapy in women who have had a hysterectomy carries less risk.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Early Detection</h2>
<h3>Mammography</h3>
<p>Screening mammography reduces breast cancer mortality by 15–20%. Recommendations vary: the American Cancer Society recommends annual screening from age 40; the US Preventive Services Task Force recommends biennial screening from 50–74. Women at high genetic risk (BRCA carriers, prior chest radiation) should discuss annual breast MRI starting at age 25–30 with their physician. Digital breast tomosynthesis (3D mammography) offers superior sensitivity, particularly in dense breast tissue, and is increasingly the standard of care.</p>
<h3>Breast Self-Awareness</h3>
<p>Monthly formal self-examination is no longer universally mandated, but knowing how your breasts normally look and feel is invaluable. Promptly report any new lump, skin dimpling, nipple retraction or bloody discharge, persistent asymmetry, or redness to a healthcare provider. Most breast cancers are painless at presentation.</p>

<h2>Symptoms</h2>
<p>Early breast cancer typically produces no symptoms — reinforcing the necessity of screening. As disease advances: a hard or soft lump in the breast or armpit; skin dimpling (peau d'orange texture); nipple inversion or bloody discharge; persistent redness, scaling, or thickening of the nipple or breast skin; or changes in breast shape or size all warrant evaluation.</p>

<h2>Diagnosis</h2>
<p>Abnormal screening findings trigger diagnostic mammography, targeted ultrasound, and — critically — core needle biopsy guided by imaging. Biopsy provides tissue for histological analysis and receptor profiling (ER, PR, HER2 status). Genomic tests such as Oncotype DX and MammaPrint analyse tumour gene expression to predict recurrence risk and guide chemotherapy decisions in HR+ disease, sparing many women unnecessary treatment. Staging integrates tumour size, lymph node status, metastases, grade, and molecular subtypes.</p>

<h2>Treatment Options</h2>
<h3>Surgery</h3>
<p>Breast-conserving surgery (lumpectomy) removes the tumour with clear margins and is equivalent to mastectomy in survival when followed by radiation. Mastectomy — unilateral or prophylactic bilateral — is appropriate for larger tumours, multiple tumour foci, BRCA mutation carriers, or patient preference. Sentinel lymph node biopsy evaluates axillary nodal status with minimal morbidity.</p>
<h3>Radiation</h3>
<p>Post-lumpectomy radiation reduces local recurrence risk by approximately two-thirds. Modern intensity-modulated techniques and hypofractionated regimens (delivering higher doses over fewer sessions) achieve equivalent outcomes with reduced toxicity and inconvenience.</p>
<h3>Systemic Therapies</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Endocrine Therapy:</strong> Tamoxifen (pre-menopausal women) and aromatase inhibitors — anastrozole, letrozole, exemestane (post-menopausal women) — substantially reduce recurrence in HR+ disease. Extended therapy for 10 years provides additional protection for high-risk patients.</li>
  <li><strong>Targeted HER2 Therapy:</strong> Trastuzumab (Herceptin) and pertuzumab in combination have dramatically improved survival in HER2+ disease. Antibody-drug conjugate trastuzumab deruxtecan (T-DXd) produces remarkable responses in metastatic HER2-low disease.</li>
  <li><strong>Chemotherapy:</strong> Anthracycline-taxane regimens are standard for TNBC, high-risk HR+, and HER2+ cancers. Neoadjuvant chemotherapy (before surgery) can downstage tumours and provides important prognostic information through pathological response assessment.</li>
  <li><strong>Immunotherapy:</strong> Pembrolizumab combined with chemotherapy is approved for PD-L1-positive TNBC in both early-stage neoadjuvant and metastatic settings, producing meaningful survival gains.</li>
  <li><strong>CDK4/6 Inhibitors:</strong> Palbociclib, ribociclib, and abemaciclib combined with endocrine therapy have substantially prolonged progression-free and overall survival in metastatic HR+ disease.</li>
  <li><strong>PARP Inhibitors:</strong> Olaparib and talazoparib exploit impaired DNA repair in BRCA-mutated cancers and are approved for both early-stage (adjuvant) and metastatic settings.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Survivorship</h2>
<p>Survivorship care encompasses ongoing surveillance (annual mammography, regular examination), management of treatment side effects (bone health with aromatase inhibitors, lymphoedema after axillary surgery), and psychological support. Exercise during and after treatment reduces fatigue and improves quality of life. Evidence increasingly supports post-treatment physical activity as a modifier of recurrence risk, particularly in HR+ disease. Reconstruction options after mastectomy have expanded considerably; decisions should be made through thorough shared decision-making before surgery.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>Do men get breast cancer?</h3>
<p>Yes — male breast cancer accounts for about 1% of all cases. Risk factors include BRCA2 mutations, Klinefelter syndrome, obesity, and elevated oestrogen levels. Men are frequently diagnosed at later stages due to lower awareness, but stage-for-stage prognosis is comparable to women.</p>
<h3>Is every breast lump cancerous?</h3>
<p>No. The majority of breast lumps are benign — fibroadenomas, cysts, or fibrocystic changes are common. However, any new or changing lump deserves prompt medical evaluation. Only biopsy can definitively rule out malignancy.</p>
<h3>Does breastfeeding reduce risk?</h3>
<p>Yes. Cumulative breastfeeding for ≥12 months is associated with approximately 4% risk reduction per year of breastfeeding, with additional benefit per birth. The mechanism involves delayed resumption of menstrual cycles and differentiation of breast tissue.</p>
<h3>How long does treatment last?</h3>
<p>Early-stage treatment spans approximately 6–12 months for active therapy (surgery, radiation, and chemotherapy if required), followed by 5–10 years of endocrine therapy for HR+ disease. Long-term surveillance continues for decades.</p>
<h3>What is genetic counselling and who should consider it?</h3>
<p>Genetic counselling evaluates personal and family history to assess hereditary cancer syndrome probability and guide testing decisions. It is recommended for women with early-onset breast cancer, bilateral disease, ovarian cancer, multiple affected relatives, or male breast cancer in the family. Identifying a BRCA mutation informs both personal management and enables testing of at-risk relatives.</p>

<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul>
  <li>World Health Organization. Breast Cancer fact sheet. 2023.</li>
  <li>American Cancer Society. Breast Cancer Facts and Figures 2022–2024.</li>
  <li>Cardoso F, et al. Early breast cancer: ESMO Clinical Practice Guidelines. Annals of Oncology. 2019.</li>
  <li>NCCN. Breast Cancer Guidelines. Version 2023.</li>
  <li>Mayo Clinic. Breast cancer — Diagnosis and treatment. 2023.</li>
</ul>`;

const anxietyDisorders = `
<p>Anxiety disorders are the most prevalent category of mental health conditions worldwide, affecting an estimated 284 million people according to the World Health Organization. Despite their ubiquity, they remain underdiagnosed and undertreated — frequently mistaken for personality traits, physical illness, or simple worry. This matters because anxiety disorders are among the most treatable psychiatric conditions, with multiple evidence-based interventions proven effective in high-quality randomised trials.</p>

<h2>Anxiety vs. Anxiety Disorder</h2>
<p>Anxiety is a normal, adaptive response to perceived threat — it sharpens focus, mobilises energy, and prepares the body to act. An anxiety disorder represents a pathological intensification of this response: excessive, persistent, poorly controlled anxiety that is disproportionate to the actual threat and significantly interferes with daily functioning. The critical distinguishing dimensions are frequency, duration, intensity, and functional impact — not the presence of anxiety itself.</p>

<h2>Types of Anxiety Disorders</h2>
<h3>Generalised Anxiety Disorder (GAD)</h3>
<p>GAD involves persistent, difficult-to-control worry about multiple life domains — health, finances, work, relationships, and minor matters — lasting at least six months and accompanied by physical symptoms: muscle tension, fatigue, irritability, difficulty concentrating, and disturbed sleep. It affects approximately 3% of the population and is twice as common in women.</p>
<h3>Panic Disorder</h3>
<p>Recurrent, unexpected panic attacks — sudden surges of intense fear peaking within minutes — characterised by heart pounding, chest tightness, shortness of breath, dizziness, and a terrifying sense of impending doom. Anticipatory anxiety about future attacks and avoidance of situations associated with past episodes can progressively restrict daily life.</p>
<h3>Social Anxiety Disorder</h3>
<p>Marked fear of scrutiny and negative evaluation in social or performance situations that leads to active avoidance of social, educational, and occupational opportunities. It is the third most common mental health condition globally and frequently goes unrecognised for years, mistaken for shyness or introversion.</p>
<h3>Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD)</h3>
<p>Develops following exposure to actual or threatened death, serious injury, or sexual violence. Core features include intrusive re-experiencing (flashbacks, nightmares), persistent avoidance of trauma reminders, negative alterations in cognition and mood, and hyperarousal. PTSD affects approximately 7–8% of the population across a lifetime.</p>
<h3>Specific Phobias and OCD</h3>
<p>Specific phobias involve intense, immediate fear of particular objects or situations out of proportion to actual danger. Obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) — now classified separately — involves intrusive, unwanted thoughts (obsessions) and repetitive behaviours (compulsions) performed to reduce distress.</p>

<h2>Causes and Risk Factors</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Neurobiological:</strong> Dysregulation of the amygdala (threat detection), prefrontal cortical control circuits, and neurotransmitter systems — serotonin, norepinephrine, GABA — underlie pathological anxiety.</li>
  <li><strong>Genetic:</strong> Heritability estimates range from 30–67%. No single "anxiety gene" exists; multiple genetic variants interact with environmental exposures to modulate vulnerability.</li>
  <li><strong>Early Adversity:</strong> Childhood trauma, abuse, neglect, or attachment disruption sensitises the stress response system and significantly elevates lifetime anxiety risk.</li>
  <li><strong>Temperament:</strong> Behavioural inhibition in early childhood — fearfulness and withdrawal in novel situations — is a robust developmental precursor to anxiety disorders.</li>
  <li><strong>Medical Conditions:</strong> Thyroid dysfunction, cardiac arrhythmias, and certain medications can precipitate or mimic anxiety symptoms, requiring careful evaluation before a primary anxiety disorder is assumed.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Evidence-Based Treatments</h2>
<h3>Cognitive Behavioural Therapy (CBT)</h3>
<p>CBT is the gold-standard psychological treatment for anxiety disorders, backed by hundreds of randomised controlled trials. The cognitive component identifies and restructures distorted thinking patterns — catastrophising, probability overestimation, and emotional reasoning. The behavioural component, particularly exposure therapy, systematically confronts feared situations in a graded, controlled manner, extinguishing the fear response through habituation. Most protocols achieve significant and durable results in 12–20 sessions. Gains are well maintained at one and two-year follow-up, in contrast to medication, which typically loses effect when discontinued.</p>
<h3>Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT)</h3>
<p>ACT shifts the focus from eliminating anxiety to building a meaningful life alongside it. Patients learn psychological defusion (observing thoughts without reacting), acceptance of uncomfortable internal states, values clarification, and values-aligned action. Evidence supports ACT as comparably effective to CBT across multiple anxiety presentations, with particular strength in GAD and social anxiety.</p>
<h3>Pharmacotherapy</h3>
<p>SSRIs (sertraline, escitalopram, fluoxetine) and SNRIs (venlafaxine, duloxetine) are first-line medications across most anxiety disorder subtypes. Full therapeutic effect emerges over 4–6 weeks; treatment is typically continued for 6–12 months after remission before gradual tapering. Buspirone offers anxiolytic benefit without dependence risk, particularly in GAD. Beta-blockers manage peripheral physical symptoms (palpitations, trembling) situationally. Benzodiazepines provide rapid relief but carry tolerance, dependence, and cognitive impairment risks — restricted to short-term use in specific clinical situations.</p>
<h3>Mindfulness-Based Interventions</h3>
<p>Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction (MBSR) and Mindfulness-Based Cognitive Therapy (MBCT) cultivate sustained, non-judgmental attention to present experience, interrupting the future-oriented worry cycle central to anxiety. Meta-analyses confirm moderate-to-large effect sizes across anxiety disorder subtypes. Regular practice of 10–20 minutes daily produces measurable structural changes in anxiety-related brain regions within weeks.</p>

<h2>Self-Management Strategies</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Diaphragmatic Breathing:</strong> Slow breathing (4-count inhale, 6-count exhale) activates the parasympathetic nervous system, directly counteracting physiological arousal within minutes.</li>
  <li><strong>Regular Aerobic Exercise:</strong> Meta-analyses place exercise efficacy for anxiety comparable to medication. Mechanisms include endorphin release, BDNF upregulation, improved sleep, and reduced cortisol reactivity.</li>
  <li><strong>Sleep Consistency:</strong> Anxiety and insomnia are bidirectionally linked. Consistent sleep-wake times, a dark and cool environment, and a screen-free wind-down routine address both simultaneously.</li>
  <li><strong>Limiting Caffeine and Alcohol:</strong> Caffeine directly stimulates the sympathetic nervous system. Alcohol reduces anxiety acutely but reliably worsens it during metabolism and disrupts sleep architecture.</li>
  <li><strong>Structured Worry Time:</strong> Postponing intrusive worries to a designated 15-minute daily window reduces their pervasiveness throughout the day.</li>
</ul>

<h2>When to Seek Professional Help</h2>
<p>Professional evaluation is warranted when anxiety is present most days for two or more weeks, significantly interfering with work, relationships, or daily activities, accompanied by substance use to cope, or associated with panic attacks. Urgent evaluation is needed if anxiety co-occurs with suicidal thoughts or self-harm urges. Anxiety disorders respond strongly to early intervention — do not wait for symptoms to become severe before seeking care.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>Is anxiety "just in your head"?</h3>
<p>No — anxiety disorders have measurable neurobiological underpinnings including identifiable changes in brain circuitry, neurotransmitter function, and the HPA stress axis. They cause quantifiable physical symptoms and functional impairment. This phrase reflects a fundamental misunderstanding of how deeply brain and body are integrated.</p>
<h3>Will I need medication for life?</h3>
<p>Not necessarily. Many patients achieve lasting remission through CBT alone. Those who require medication typically use it for 6–12 months after achieving remission, then taper gradually. Some with severe or recurrent presentations benefit from longer-term pharmacotherapy. The decision is individualised based on severity, recurrence history, and patient preference.</p>
<h3>Can anxiety cause physical illness?</h3>
<p>Yes. Chronic anxiety sustains a state of physiological stress that contributes to cardiovascular disease, immune dysregulation, gastrointestinal disorders (including IBS), insomnia, and chronic pain syndromes. The gut-brain axis is particularly bidirectional — anxiety commonly manifests with gastrointestinal symptoms, and gut microbiome disruption can in turn modulate anxiety through the vagus nerve.</p>
<h3>How long does CBT take?</h3>
<p>Most CBT protocols for anxiety disorders are delivered in 12–20 weekly sessions. Specific phobias and panic disorder may respond faster (6–12 sessions). Between-session practice is essential; the exposure component does its most active work outside of therapy sessions.</p>
<h3>Can children have anxiety disorders?</h3>
<p>Yes — anxiety disorders are among the most prevalent childhood mental health conditions. Separation anxiety, GAD, social anxiety, and specific phobias commonly begin in childhood. Developmentally adapted CBT is highly effective. Early identification and treatment are important: untreated childhood anxiety frequently persists into adulthood and increases risk for depression.</p>

<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul>
  <li>World Health Organization. Mental disorders fact sheet. 2022.</li>
  <li>American Psychiatric Association. DSM-5-TR. 2022.</li>
  <li>Bandelow B, et al. Treatment of anxiety disorders. Dialogues in Clinical Neuroscience. 2017.</li>
  <li>Hofmann SG, et al. The Efficacy of CBT: A Review of Meta-analyses. Cognitive Therapy and Research. 2012.</li>
  <li>NIMH. Anxiety Disorders. 2023.</li>
</ul>`;

const mediterraneanDiet = `
<p>Few dietary patterns have earned as consistent and compelling a scientific endorsement as the Mediterranean diet. Named for the traditional eating habits of populations bordering the Mediterranean Sea in the mid-20th century, the pattern was brought to scientific attention by Ancel Keys' landmark Seven Countries Study, which identified dramatically lower cardiovascular mortality in Greece and southern Italy compared to northern Europe and the United States — despite moderate fat intake. Decades of subsequent research have confirmed and expanded these observations, establishing the Mediterranean diet as one of the most evidence-based approaches to long-term health available.</p>

<h2>What Is the Mediterranean Diet?</h2>
<p>The Mediterranean diet is best understood as a flexible dietary pattern defined by food groups and their proportions — not a rigid meal plan. UNESCO recognised it as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity in 2010, acknowledging both its nutritional value and its broader cultural significance as a way of living, not merely eating. The pattern emphasises whole, minimally processed foods; abundant plant diversity; healthy unsaturated fats as the primary culinary fat; and moderate fish consumption, with limited red meat and refined carbohydrates.</p>

<h2>Core Food Groups</h2>
<h3>Daily Foundation</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Vegetables and Fruits:</strong> At minimum 5–7 portions daily. Traditional Mediterranean populations consumed remarkable variety — tomatoes, leafy greens, aubergine, courgette, artichokes, peppers, citrus, figs, pomegranates — providing extensive phytonutrients, fibre, vitamins, and minerals.</li>
  <li><strong>Whole Grains and Legumes:</strong> Bread, pasta, couscous, bulgur, and polenta in whole-grain form; lentils, chickpeas, white beans, and fava beans several times weekly. These provide sustained energy, soluble fibre (which lowers LDL), and plant-based protein.</li>
  <li><strong>Extra-Virgin Olive Oil (EVOO):</strong> The cornerstone fat, used generously for cooking and as a dressing — typically 3–4 tablespoons daily. EVOO contains oleic acid (a cardioprotective monounsaturated fat) and over 30 polyphenolic compounds with potent anti-inflammatory and antioxidant activity, including oleocanthal and oleuropein.</li>
  <li><strong>Nuts and Seeds:</strong> Almonds, walnuts, hazelnuts — a small handful daily. Associated with reductions in LDL, inflammation, and all-cause mortality in large meta-analyses.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Weekly Foods</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Fish and Seafood (≥2×/week):</strong> Fatty fish — sardines, mackerel, anchovies, salmon, tuna — provide EPA and DHA omega-3 fatty acids that lower triglycerides, reduce inflammatory cytokines, and decrease arrhythmia risk.</li>
  <li><strong>Poultry, Eggs, and Dairy:</strong> Moderate portions of poultry several times weekly. Dairy primarily as fermented forms — yogurt, kefir, and aged cheeses — which provide beneficial microbiota-modulating effects alongside calcium and protein.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Rare Foods</h3>
<p>Red and processed meats are limited to a few times monthly. Sweets, refined carbohydrates, and ultra-processed foods are occasional indulgences, not daily staples. This displacement of inflammatory foods is as important as the additions.</p>

<h2>Cardiovascular Evidence</h2>
<p>The PREDIMED trial — a landmark randomised controlled trial involving 7,447 high-cardiovascular-risk participants followed for a median of 4.8 years — found that the Mediterranean diet supplemented with EVOO or mixed nuts reduced the composite endpoint of myocardial infarction, stroke, and cardiovascular death by 30% relative to a low-fat control diet. The PREDIMED-Plus follow-up, incorporating energy restriction and physical activity within a Mediterranean framework, demonstrated further benefit. These findings are supported by the Lyon Diet Heart Study (73% cardiovascular event reduction in secondary prevention), and by consistent results from large prospective cohort studies across multiple populations and countries.</p>

<h2>Cancer Prevention</h2>
<p>High adherence to the Mediterranean diet is associated with a 10–12% reduction in overall cancer incidence in large cohort data. The most robust evidence exists for colorectal cancer (approximately 20% risk reduction), breast cancer in post-menopausal women, gastric cancer, and hepatocellular carcinoma. Mechanisms include anti-inflammatory polyphenols, fibre-mediated gut microbiome modulation, antioxidant protection against DNA damage, and reduced insulin resistance — a promoter of proliferative signalling across multiple cancer types.</p>

<h2>Brain Health and Cognitive Ageing</h2>
<p>The MIND diet — a hybrid of the Mediterranean and DASH diets specifically optimised for neuroprotection — has been associated with up to 53% lower rates of Alzheimer's disease in high-adherence participants in observational research. Prospective cohort studies consistently show slower cognitive decline in those with higher Mediterranean diet adherence. The biological mechanisms are compelling: EPA/DHA omega-3s maintain neuronal membrane fluidity and reduce neuroinflammation; polyphenols (especially from EVOO and berries) cross the blood-brain barrier and support synaptic plasticity; B vitamins lower homocysteine — an independent risk factor for brain atrophy; and antioxidant vitamins (E, C) protect against oxidative stress in long-lived neurons.</p>

<h2>Metabolic and Weight Benefits</h2>
<p>Despite its moderate fat content, the Mediterranean diet supports healthy weight maintenance rather than gain. High dietary fibre from vegetables, legumes, and whole grains promotes satiety. Its anti-inflammatory effects improve insulin sensitivity and adiponectin signalling. A 2016 meta-analysis of 19 randomised trials found Mediterranean diet adherents achieved comparable weight loss to other dietary patterns with superior improvements in fasting glucose and HDL cholesterol — the "best of both worlds" metabolically.</p>

<h2>Getting Started</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Replace refined with whole grains:</strong> Swap white bread for whole-grain sourdough, white rice for farro or bulgur, standard pasta for legume pasta.</li>
  <li><strong>Build meals around vegetables:</strong> Use a plate method — half the plate vegetables and salad, one quarter whole grain, one quarter protein.</li>
  <li><strong>Switch to EVOO:</strong> Replace butter and seed oils with quality extra-virgin olive oil for all cooking and dressings.</li>
  <li><strong>Plan two fish meals weekly:</strong> Affordable options: canned sardines, mackerel, and wild salmon are nutritionally equivalent to fresh and significantly cheaper.</li>
  <li><strong>Snack on nuts:</strong> Replace processed snacks with a small handful of mixed nuts (approximately 30 g / 1 oz).</li>
  <li><strong>Eat socially and slowly:</strong> The Mediterranean diet encompasses a broader lifestyle — communal, unhurried meals, seasonal eating, and daily movement. These contextual elements may amplify the dietary benefits beyond what nutrient composition alone predicts.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>Is the Mediterranean diet suitable for vegetarians?</h3>
<p>Easily adapted. The diet is already predominantly plant-based; fish and poultry are simply expanded with more legumes, tofu, tempeh, eggs, and dairy. Attention to omega-3 status (flaxseed, chia, walnuts, or algae-based DHA/EPA supplementation) and vitamin B12 is appropriate for vegetarians and vegans.</p>
<h3>Is wine required?</h3>
<p>No. While moderate red wine consumption is traditional, growing recognition of alcohol's role in cancer risk has shifted major health organisations away from recommending any alcohol for health. The non-alcoholic components of the diet account for the documented benefits. Pomegranate juice or sparkling water with meals are compatible substitutes.</p>
<h3>Is it expensive?</h3>
<p>Not necessarily. The pattern's emphasis on legumes, seasonal vegetables, whole grains, and eggs makes it highly economical. Canned fish, dried lentils, and seasonal produce significantly reduce costs. A 2019 systematic review found the Mediterranean diet is cost-competitive with standard Western dietary patterns when plant proteins substitute for expensive animal proteins.</p>
<h3>How quickly do health benefits appear?</h3>
<p>Blood pressure and inflammatory marker improvements can appear within 4–8 weeks. Lipid profile changes take 6–12 weeks. Long-term outcomes — cardiovascular events, cancer risk reduction, cognitive trajectory — manifest over years of sustained adherence, as demonstrated in the PREDIMED and MIND diet cohort studies.</p>
<h3>What is the difference between Mediterranean and DASH diets?</h3>
<p>Both patterns share abundant plant foods, whole grains, lean proteins, and limited sodium and saturated fat. DASH imposes stricter sodium limits and higher dairy recommendations, designed specifically for blood pressure reduction. The Mediterranean diet is more permissive of healthy fats (especially EVOO and nuts) and traditionally includes moderate alcohol. For overall cardiovascular health and longevity, both perform comparably; for strict blood pressure management, DASH has the most direct evidence.</p>

<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Estruch R, et al. Primary Prevention of CVD with a Mediterranean Diet. NEJM. 2018.</li>
  <li>Martínez-González MA, et al. PREDIMED-Plus trial. J Intern Med. 2021.</li>
  <li>Morris MC, et al. MIND diet and Alzheimer's disease incidence. Alzheimers Dement. 2015.</li>
  <li>World Cancer Research Fund. Diet, Nutrition, Physical Activity and Cancer. 2018.</li>
  <li>Mayo Clinic. Mediterranean diet: A heart-healthy eating plan. 2023.</li>
</ul>`;

const migraine = `
<p>Migraine is one of the most disabling neurological conditions in existence, affecting approximately one billion people worldwide. The Global Burden of Disease Study consistently ranks migraine as the second leading cause of disability globally — yet it remains profoundly underdiagnosed, undertreated, and misunderstood. The characterisation of migraine as "just a bad headache" fundamentally fails the reality of those for whom attacks mean hours or days of incapacitating pain, sensory hypersensitivity, nausea, and neurological disturbance. Understanding migraine as a legitimate neurological disease is the foundation of effective management.</p>

<h2>Migraine vs. Other Headache Disorders</h2>
<p>Migraine is not simply a severe headache. It is a complex neurological event characterised by unilateral, pulsating, moderate-to-severe head pain worsened by routine physical activity, combined with nausea or vomiting and/or marked sensitivity to light and sound. Tension-type headache — bilateral, pressing, not aggravated by movement — lacks these associated features and rarely causes the profound functional disability that migraine produces. The distinction matters clinically because treatments effective for one are frequently ineffective for the other.</p>

<h2>The Four Phases of a Migraine Attack</h2>
<h3>Prodrome</h3>
<p>Up to 60% of migraineurs experience prodromal symptoms 24–48 hours before head pain begins. These include mood changes (depression, euphoria, irritability), food cravings, neck stiffness, yawning, increased urination, and fatigue. Recognising the prodrome enables early treatment initiation, which substantially improves outcomes by aborting attacks before central sensitisation becomes established.</p>
<h3>Aura</h3>
<p>Approximately 25–30% of migraineurs experience aura — transient, fully reversible focal neurological symptoms developing gradually over 5–20 minutes and resolving within 60 minutes. Visual aura is most common, producing a "scintillating scotoma" — an expanding arc of shimmering, zigzag light that begins near central vision and spreads peripherally. Sensory aura (numbness or tingling spreading across the face and arm), speech disturbance, and rarely motor weakness (hemiplegic migraine) also occur. Aura reflects cortical spreading depression — a slow wave of neuronal depolarisation propagating across the cerebral cortex.</p>
<h3>Headache Phase</h3>
<p>Lasting 4–72 hours without treatment, the headache phase features unilateral (in about 60% of attacks), pulsating, moderate-to-severe pain worsened by movement. Nausea affects approximately 80% of patients; vomiting about 30%. Photophobia and phonophobia are near-universal. Osmophobia (smell sensitivity) affects over 40%. Most patients seek a dark, quiet environment; sleep, if achievable, can abort or substantially reduce the attack.</p>
<h3>Postdrome</h3>
<p>The "migraine hangover" following headache resolution includes cognitive slowing, fatigue, weakness, persistent light sensitivity, and mood changes lasting up to 48 hours. This phase contributes significantly to overall migraine-related disability and is increasingly recognised as a distinct clinical component requiring attention.</p>

<h2>Common Migraine Triggers</h2>
<p>Triggers do not cause migraine — they lower the threshold for attacks in neurologically predisposed individuals. Identifying and managing personal triggers is a fundamental preventive strategy:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Sleep disruption:</strong> Both sleep deprivation and excessive sleep reliably trigger attacks. Consistent sleep-wake times (including weekends) are among the highest-yield preventive strategies.</li>
  <li><strong>Hormonal fluctuations:</strong> The perimenstrual oestrogen drop triggers attacks in 50–60% of women with migraine. Oral contraceptives containing oestrogen can increase frequency and, in women with aura, carry elevated stroke risk.</li>
  <li><strong>Stress and stress release:</strong> The "weekend migraine" phenomenon reflects attacks occurring during relaxation following sustained psychological stress.</li>
  <li><strong>Dietary triggers:</strong> Skipping meals and dehydration are reliable triggers. Alcohol (particularly red wine and beer), caffeine excess and withdrawal, aged cheeses, processed meats with nitrates, and MSG affect susceptible individuals.</li>
  <li><strong>Sensory stimuli:</strong> Bright or flickering lights, strong perfumes, loud sounds, and barometric pressure changes are widely reported triggers.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Acute Treatment</h2>
<h3>NSAIDs and Combination Analgesics</h3>
<p>For mild-to-moderate attacks, ibuprofen 400–600 mg, naproxen sodium 500 mg, or aspirin 900 mg (with antiemetics if needed) are effective first-line options. Combination products containing acetaminophen, aspirin, and caffeine (e.g., Excedrin) demonstrate superiority over individual components. Critical: using acute analgesics more than 10–15 days per month risks medication overuse headache — a paradoxical condition of increased headache frequency driven by treatment overuse.</p>
<h3>Triptans</h3>
<p>Serotonin 5-HT1B/1D receptor agonists — sumatriptan, rizatriptan, eletriptan, zolmitriptan, almotriptan, frovatriptan, naratriptan — are migraine-specific agents that constrict dilated intracranial blood vessels, block CGRP release from trigeminal terminals, and modulate brainstem pain processing. Oral triptans are most convenient; subcutaneous sumatriptan provides fastest onset (10–15 minutes) for severe attacks with early nausea. Contraindicated in uncontrolled hypertension and ischaemic cardiovascular or cerebrovascular disease.</p>
<h3>CGRP Antagonists (Gepants) and Lasmiditan</h3>
<p>Ubrogepant and rimegepant — small-molecule CGRP receptor antagonists — offer effective acute treatment without vasoconstriction, making them safe for patients with cardiovascular contraindications to triptans. Rimegepant also demonstrates preventive benefit taken every other day. Lasmiditan, a selective 5-HT1F agonist, is another vasoconstrictive-free option, though its CNS side effects require a waiting period before driving.</p>

<h2>Preventive Treatment</h2>
<p>Preventive therapy is indicated when attacks occur ≥4 days per month, when acute medications are inadequate or overused, or when attacks are severely disabling. Goal: ≥50% reduction in monthly migraine days.</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Anti-CGRP Monoclonal Antibodies:</strong> Erenumab, fremanezumab, galcanezumab (monthly or quarterly subcutaneous injection) and eptinezumab (quarterly IV infusion) are the first migraine-specific preventive class. They achieve ≥50% response rates in 50–65% of patients with excellent tolerability and minimal drug interactions — a transformative advance for the field.</li>
  <li><strong>Topiramate and Valproate:</strong> Established anticonvulsant preventives with decades of evidence. Topiramate carries cognitive side effects requiring slow titration; valproate is teratogenic and generally avoided in women of childbearing potential.</li>
  <li><strong>Beta-Blockers:</strong> Propranolol and metoprolol remain first-generation preventives with solid evidence and broad tolerability.</li>
  <li><strong>Amitriptyline:</strong> Low-dose tricyclic antidepressant particularly useful when migraine co-occurs with insomnia or depression.</li>
  <li><strong>OnabotulinumtoxinA (Botox):</strong> Injected at 31 sites across the head and neck every 12 weeks, approved specifically for chronic migraine (≥15 headache days/month).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Non-Pharmacological Approaches</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Lifestyle regularity:</strong> Consistent sleep, regular meals, hydration, and daily moderate exercise reduce overall attack burden in most patients.</li>
  <li><strong>Biofeedback and relaxation training:</strong> Thermal biofeedback produces migraine frequency reductions comparable to medications in randomised trials, without side effects — particularly valuable for children and pregnant patients.</li>
  <li><strong>Cognitive Behavioural Therapy:</strong> Adapted for chronic headache, CBT reduces disability, catastrophising, and co-occurring anxiety and depression.</li>
  <li><strong>Neuromodulation devices:</strong> Non-invasive transcranial magnetic stimulation (nTMS) and external trigeminal nerve stimulation are FDA-cleared for acute and preventive migraine treatment.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>Is migraine hereditary?</h3>
<p>Strongly so. First-degree relatives of migraineurs have 50% higher risk than the general population. Familial hemiplegic migraine has identified specific ion channel mutations, providing a genetic window into broader migraine mechanisms.</p>
<h3>Can hormonal contraceptives worsen migraine?</h3>
<p>Combined oral contraceptives (oestrogen + progestin) can increase migraine frequency and, in women with migraine with aura, elevate ischaemic stroke risk approximately 6-fold. Current guidelines advise against combined hormonal contraception for women with migraine with aura. Progestin-only options and non-hormonal contraceptives are generally safe.</p>
<h3>What is medication overuse headache?</h3>
<p>Overuse headache occurs when acute treatments are used more than 10–15 days per month for over three months, inducing neuroplastic changes that lower the headache threshold — paradoxically increasing headache frequency. It is treated by withdrawing the overused medication, with predictable initial worsening before improvement over 2–4 weeks.</p>
<h3>Do children get migraines?</h3>
<p>Yes. Migraine affects approximately 10% of school-age children. Paediatric attacks tend to be shorter, more frequently bilateral, and more prominently associated with nausea and abdominal pain. Cyclical vomiting syndrome and abdominal migraine in children are now recognised migraine spectrum conditions. Biofeedback, CBT, and pharmacological preventives (topiramate, amitriptyline) are effective.</p>
<h3>Is there a cure?</h3>
<p>No cure exists at present, but migraine is a manageable condition for most patients with appropriate treatment. The anti-CGRP monoclonal antibodies produce complete or near-complete freedom from attacks in a meaningful proportion of previously treatment-resistant patients. Migraine frequently decreases in frequency and severity after age 50, particularly for women after menopause.</p>

<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Ashina M. Migraine. NEJM. 2020;383(19):1866–1876.</li>
  <li>GBD 2019 Disease and Injuries Collaborators. Lancet. 2020.</li>
  <li>Diener HC, et al. European Headache Federation guideline for acute migraine management. J Headache Pain. 2019.</li>
  <li>World Health Organization. Headache disorders fact sheet. 2016.</li>
  <li>Mayo Clinic. Migraine — Symptoms and causes. 2023.</li>
</ul>`;

